IPL 2025 Dream Squad Data-Driven Selection Project

Introduction

This notebook presents a complete end-to-end data-driven analysis to create the best possible IPL 2025 squad, optimized for maximum impact and balanced composition.
Using advanced data analytics, we evaluated players on key performance metrics such as total impact score, auction price efficiency, and versatility.

Project Objectives

  • Build a 15-member squad under a strict 100 Cr budget.
  • Maintain a maximum of 5 overseas players, as per IPL playing rules.
  • Optimize squad for a balanced combination of:
    • Top-order anchors
    • Explosive middle-order hitters
    • Versatile all-rounders
    • Lethal pacers & spinners
  • Allocate role-wise budget smartly (Batsmen: 50 Cr, All-rounders: 20 Cr, Bowlers: 30 Cr) to achieve the perfect balance.

Approach

  • Analyze player impact scores and auction prices.
  • Sort players impact-wise to maximize match-winning potential.
  • Use custom algorithms to control budget, role balance, and overseas constraints.
  • Assign final playing positions based on performance style and specialization.

Outcome

The final squad represents a perfect blend of stability, aggression, flexibility, and bowling strength, fully ready to dominate the 2025 IPL season.
With clear player roles and professional squad composition, this team is built to win under any conditions.

Let's dive in and build the ultimate champion squad!

def assign_bowler_type(row):
    if row['Type'] == 'BOWL' or row['Type'] == 'AR':
        if row['Player Name'] in pacer_names:
            return 'Pacer'
        else:

    else:

IPL 2025 Dream Squad Data-driven Auction Strategy

This squad has been built using a fully data-driven, professional auction strategy approach. The total budget of 100 Cr has been thoughtfully divided role-wise to balance impact, experience, and price efficiency:

  • Batsmen: 50 Cr for 6 top impactful batters
  • All-rounders: 20 Cr for 4 dynamic all-rounders
  • Bowlers: 30 Cr for 5 match-winning bowlers

Key Constraints: Max 5 overseas players to maintain team balance and adhere to IPL rules Prioritize highest Total Impact score while respecting role-wise budget Strict total squad budget cap: 100 Cr Exactly 15 players to create a full competitive squad

This approach ensures we get a well-rounded, powerful, and versatile squad capable of tackling any situation in the tournament. The selection focuses on maximizing overall team impact while optimizing for price and overseas slots.

Lets build the ultimate champion squad!

ChakDeIPL #AuctionStrategy #DreamTeam2025

In[]:
# Role-wise constraints
budget_bat = 50
budget_ar = 20
budget_bowl = 30

count_bat = 6
count_ar = 4
count_bowl = 5

max_overseas = 5

# Role-wise player pools
bat_df = df[df['Type'] == 'BAT'].sort_values('Total_Impact', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
ar_df = df[df['Type'] == 'AR'].sort_values('Total_Impact', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
bowl_df = df[df['Type'] == 'BOWL'].sort_values('Total_Impact', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

selected_players = []
total_price = 0.0
overseas_count = 0

# Helper function to select players from role
def select_role(df_role, role_count, role_budget, overseas_count, total_price, max_overseas):
    role_players = []
    used_budget = 0.0
    for _, row in df_role.iterrows():
        price = row['Sold']
        overseas = row['Overseas']

        # Check overseas
        if overseas == 'Yes' and overseas_count >= max_overseas:
            continue

        # Check role budget
        if used_budget + price > role_budget:
            continue

        # Check overall budget
        if total_price + price > 100:
            continue

        # Add player
        role_players.append(row.to_dict())
        used_budget += price
        total_price += price
        if overseas == 'Yes':
            overseas_count += 1

        # Stop if role count done
        if len(role_players) == role_count:
            break
    return role_players, used_budget, overseas_count, total_price

# --- Select batsmen ---
bat_players, spent_bat, overseas_count, total_price = select_role(bat_df, count_bat, budget_bat, overseas_count, total_price, max_overseas)

# --- Select all-rounders ---
ar_players, spent_ar, overseas_count, total_price = select_role(ar_df, count_ar, budget_ar, overseas_count, total_price, max_overseas)

# --- Select bowlers ---
bowl_players, spent_bowl, overseas_count, total_price = select_role(bowl_df, count_bowl, budget_bowl, overseas_count, total_price, max_overseas)

# Combine all
selected_players = bat_players + ar_players + bowl_players

# Create DataFrame
final_team_df = pd.DataFrame(selected_players)

# Add squad index
final_team_df.index = range(1, len(final_team_df) + 1)

# Display final team
display(final_team_df[['Player Name', 'Type', 'Team', 'Total_Impact', 'Sold', 'Overseas']])

# Print summary
print(f" Total Team Price: {round(total_price, 2)} Cr")
print(f" Batsmen Spend: {round(spent_bat, 2)} Cr for {len(bat_players)} players")
print(f" All-rounders Spend: {round(spent_ar, 2)} Cr for {len(ar_players)} players")
print(f" Bowlers Spend: {round(spent_bowl, 2)} Cr for {len(bowl_players)} players")
print(f" Total Overseas Players: {overseas_count}")
print(f" Total Squad Size: {len(final_team_df)}")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.patches as patches

# Figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 10))
ax.axis("off")
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#f7f7f7')

# Title
plt.title(" IPL 2025 Dream Squad  Final Ordered Poster", fontsize=18, weight='bold', pad=20)

# Card settings
y_start = 1.0
y_step = 0.06

for i, row in final_team_df.iterrows():
    y = y_start - i * y_step
    box_color = '#4CAF50' if row['Overseas'] == 'No' else '#FFC107'

    # Background card
    ax.add_patch(patches.Rectangle((0.05, y - 0.04), 0.9, 0.05, color=box_color, alpha=0.2, edgecolor='grey', linewidth=1.2))

    text = f"{row['Position']}. {row['Player Name']}  |  Impact: {row['Total_Impact']}  |  {row['Sold']} Cr  |  {row['Position']}  |  {'Overseas' if row['Overseas']=='Yes' else 'Indian'}"
    plt.text(0.06, y - 0.02, text, fontsize=11, va='center', ha='left', color='black', fontweight='bold')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
